## 6. Public API

### 6.1 The opaque `Secret` struct

```elixir
defmodule RotatingSecrets.Secret do
  @enforce_keys [:name, :value, :meta]
  defstruct [:name, :value, :meta]
  @opaque t :: %__MODULE__{name: atom(), value: binary(), meta: map()}

  @spec expose(t()) :: binary()
  def expose(%__MODULE__{value: v}), do: v

  @spec meta(t()) :: map()
  def meta(%__MODULE__{meta: m}), do: m

  @spec name(t()) :: atom()
  def name(%__MODULE__{name: n}), do: n

  defimpl Inspect do
    def inspect(%{name: n}, _), do: "#RotatingSecrets.Secret<#{n}:redacted>"
  end

  defimpl String.Chars do
    def to_string(_), do: raise ArgumentError,
      "cannot stringify a Secret; use RotatingSecrets.Secret.expose/1 explicitly"
  end

  defimpl Jason.Encoder do
    def encode(_, _), do: raise Protocol.UndefinedError,
      protocol: Jason.Encoder,
      value: "a Secret; use RotatingSecrets.Secret.expose/1 explicitly"
  end
end
```

**Requirements:**
- `Inspect`, `String.Chars`, `Jason.Encoder` MUST NOT expose the value.
- Attempted JSON encoding MUST raise. Silent success would mask the leak of a field that was *meant* to serialize.
- If `Phoenix` is available (detected at compile time via `Code.ensure_loaded?/1`), a `Phoenix.Param` impl MUST be generated that raises similarly.
- `expose/1` is the only way to retrieve the value. Deliberately greppable: a code review can `grep expose` to audit every value-use site.
- The struct is `@opaque` at the type level and is documented as constructible only by source implementations. Runtime enforcement is not possible in Elixir, but the type system discourages direct construction.

### 6.2 Core read API

```elixir
@spec current(name :: atom()) :: {:ok, Secret.t()} | {:error, term()}
@spec current!(name :: atom()) :: Secret.t()
```

Returns the currently-held value for `name`. Implementation is a synchronous `GenServer.call` to the Registry process for that name. Must be fast (no I/O on the hot path; the Registry serves from memory).

### 6.3 Scoped borrow

```elixir
@spec with_secret(name :: atom(), (Secret.t() -> result)) :: {:ok, result} | {:error, term()}
    when result: var
```

Executes `fun` with the current secret. Because Elixir data is immutable, this is semantically equivalent to `current/1` + passing to `fun`, but the API shape makes "this is a bounded usage scope" intent visible at call sites and matches cross-language conventions.

### 6.4 Push subscription

```elixir
@spec subscribe(name :: atom()) :: {:ok, reference()} | {:error, term()}
@spec unsubscribe(reference()) :: :ok
```

Subscribers receive messages of shape:

```elixir
{:rotating_secret_rotated, reference(), name :: atom(), version :: term()}
```

The message is deliberately **name-and-version-only, never the value**. Subscribers call `current/1` to fetch the new value. This keeps the value out of the BEAM mailbox where feasible (the value crosses processes only on explicit read, not on broadcast).

Subscribers are monitored via `Process.monitor/1`; their subscription is auto-removed on `:DOWN`. This works across nodes transparently — a remote subscriber that becomes unreachable is cleaned up normally.

### 6.5 Registration & supervision

```elixir
defmodule MyApp.Application do
  def start(_, _) do
    children = [
      {RotatingSecrets.Supervisor, [
        secrets: [
          {:api_key, source: {RotatingSecrets.Source.File,
                              path: "/run/secrets/api_key",
                              refresh: :file_watch}},
          {:db_creds, source: {RotatingSecrets.Source.File,
                               path: "/run/secrets/db.env",
                               refresh: {:interval, :timer.minutes(5)}}}
        ]
      ]}
    ]
    Supervisor.start_link(children, strategy: :one_for_one)
  end
end
```

Dynamic registration:

```elixir
RotatingSecrets.register(:another, source: {RotatingSecrets.Source.Env,
                                            var: "ANOTHER_SECRET",
                                            refresh: {:interval, :timer.seconds(30)}})
```

For Horde-registered Registries (singleton secrets in a cluster):

```elixir
{RotatingSecrets.Supervisor, [
  registry_via: {Horde.Registry, MyApp.HordeRegistry},
  secrets: [...]
]}
```

The library does not depend on Horde; `registry_via` configures the via-tuple used when starting Registry processes. Users wire up Horde themselves.

### 6.6 Source behaviour

```elixir
defmodule RotatingSecrets.Source do
  @type state :: term()
  @type material :: binary()
  @type meta :: %{
    optional(:issued_at) => DateTime.t(),
    optional(:ttl_seconds) => pos_integer(),
    optional(:version) => term(),
    optional(atom()) => term()
  }

  @callback init(opts :: keyword()) :: {:ok, state} | {:error, term()}
  @callback load(state) :: {:ok, material, meta, state} | {:error, term(), state}
  @callback subscribe_changes(state) ::
    {:ok, subscription_ref :: term(), state} | :not_supported
  @callback handle_change_notification(msg :: term(), state) ::
    {:changed, state} | :ignored | {:error, term()}
  @callback terminate(state) :: :ok

  @optional_callbacks [subscribe_changes: 1, handle_change_notification: 2, terminate: 1]
end
```

Sources declare whether they support push notification. If `subscribe_changes/1` returns `:not_supported`, the Registry falls back to polling at the configured interval. Optional callbacks keep simple sources (e.g., `Memory`) tiny.

## 7. Behavior Specification

### 7.1 Refresh lifecycle

```
        init
         │
         ▼
   ┌──Loading──┐
   │           │
   │ load()    │ error on initial load
   ▼           ▼
 Valid ◄── InitFailure (Registry does not start)
   │
   │ TTL * 2/3 elapsed OR push notification
   ▼
 Refreshing
   │         │
   │ ok      │ error
   ▼         ▼
 Valid    Expiring (serve stale, backoff retry, alert)
   │         │
   │         │ TTL elapsed, still no success
   ▼         ▼
 Valid    Expired (serve stale, loud telemetry, continue retry)
```

**Requirements:**
- Initial load failure MUST return an error from `start_link/1` (or the `register/2` call). This is a deployment error and must be visible at boot.
- Post-init refresh failures MUST NOT invalidate the current value. Registry continues to serve last-known-good.
- Refresh retries use exponential backoff. Default initial 1s, cap 60s, factor 2.0. Configurable per-secret.
- TTL-driven refresh fires at 2/3 of lifetime by default, configurable per-secret.
- `Expiring` and `Expired` states emit distinct telemetry events.

### 7.2 Fail-soft guarantees

- A failed `load/1` never crashes the Registry.
- A crashed source implementation (unexpected exception) is caught, logged without value, and treated as a refresh error.
- If the source fails beyond a configurable threshold (default 3 consecutive failures), telemetry fires `:degraded`. Whether to escalate is the application's policy.
- Registry supervisor strategy is `:permanent` with `:transient` restart — under normal operation it should never exit.

### 7.3 Concurrency & consistency

- Reads (`current/1`) are serialized through the Registry GenServer. Deliberate choice over ETS: one process holds the value, not N copies across tables.
- Benchmark target: `current/1` sustains ≥50,000 reads/sec on a reference machine. If this becomes a production bottleneck, a `:persistent_term` fast-path is a candidate for v2.
- Writes (rotations) are atomic from the reader's perspective: a reader sees either the old value or the new value, never a torn value.

### 7.4 Process flags & leak prevention

- Every Registry GenServer MUST call `Process.flag(:sensitive, true)` in `init/1`. This suppresses state from crash reports, `:sys.get_state`, and `:observer`.
- The library MUST NOT log the secret value at any level (`debug`/`info`/`warn`/`error`). Tests verify this via log capture across all code paths.
- The library MUST NOT include the secret value in telemetry metadata. Events carry name, version, and non-value metadata only.

### 7.5 Telemetry events

```
[:rotating_secrets, :source, :load, :start]      %{name: atom()}
[:rotating_secrets, :source, :load, :stop]       %{name, duration_ms}
[:rotating_secrets, :source, :load, :exception]  %{name, kind, reason}
[:rotating_secrets, :rotation]                   %{name, version_old, version_new}
[:rotating_secrets, :state_change]               %{name, from, to}
[:rotating_secrets, :subscriber_added]           %{name, count}
[:rotating_secrets, :subscriber_removed]         %{name, count, reason}
[:rotating_secrets, :degraded]                   %{name, consecutive_failures}
```

No event may carry the secret value. Tests enforce via event handler assertions.

## 8. Built-in Sources

### 8.1 `RotatingSecrets.Source.File`

Reads from a file path. Two refresh modes:

- `refresh: :file_watch` — uses `FileSystem` (optional dep) to watch via inotify/FSEvents/ReadDirectoryChanges. Emits reload on `modified` and `moved_to` events.
- `refresh: {:interval, ms}` — polls file mtime, re-reads on change.

**Requirements:**
- File MUST be owner-readable only (mode 0600) or owner/group-readable (0640). Otherwise emits a warning (not an error — deployments vary and strict enforcement is a common footgun).
- Default behavior treats file content as raw secret material; trailing whitespace is stripped (common agent template artifact).
- Missing file on initial load = error. Missing file on refresh = serve stale, log, continue retrying.
- MUST handle the atomic-rename pattern correctly (Vault Agent and similar tools write to a temp file then rename). File-watch re-opens on `moved_to`.
- MUST handle platform differences: Linux inotify, macOS FSEvents, Windows ReadDirectoryChanges, BSD kqueue. File-watch tests run on Linux and macOS in CI; Windows is best-effort in v1.

### 8.2 `RotatingSecrets.Source.Env`

Reads from an environment variable. Refresh is `{:interval, ms}` only (no meaningful watch primitive for env changes). Emits a `:dev_source_in_use` warning on init — env sources are primarily for development and simple deployments, not production with rotation.

### 8.3 `RotatingSecrets.Source.Memory`

Holds a constant value. Useful for:
- Truly static secrets that don't rotate (migration scenarios).
- Test setup.
- Composition: a higher-level source that derives material from other sources.

Rotation is possible via an explicit `RotatingSecrets.Source.Memory.update/2` function; callers can trigger rotation programmatically.

## 9. Clustering & Multi-Node Deployment

### 9.1 Default: independent per-node Registries

The default and recommended shape is **N independent Registry processes, one set per node**. Each node runs its own `Supervisor`, starts its own Registries, and converges on its authoritative source independently.

This is correct because:
- The authoritative source (Vault, file rendered by local agent, etc.) is the single source of truth.
- Nodes can be in subtly different states without affecting correctness.
- Netsplits are a non-event: each side serves its last-known-good; no reconciliation on heal.

No user action required beyond starting the supervisor on each node.

### 9.2 Horde integration for singleton secrets

For cases where a secret should be owned by exactly one node at a time, Registries MUST be startable under `{:via, Horde.Registry, ...}`. See §6.5.

**Requirements:**
- The library MUST NOT hard-code `Registry` as the naming mechanism.
- On process migration (Horde moves the Registry to another node), the new process MUST re-initialize from its child_spec args and perform a fresh initial load. The child_spec MUST be fully serializable (no closures, no PIDs, no refs).
- Subscribers MUST survive Registry migration — from the subscriber's perspective, the Registry is a stable logical entity. On migration, existing subscribers receive the next rotation event normally.

### 9.3 Subscriber monitoring across nodes

Subscribers can live on different nodes than the Registry owning their secret.

**Requirements:**
- Subscriber monitoring uses `Process.monitor/1` (works across distributed Erlang).
- On `{:DOWN, ...}` with `:noconnection` reason, the Registry removes the subscriber and emits telemetry.
- On `:nodedown`, the Registry bulk-removes all subscribers from that node efficiently (≤O(n) where n is subscribers-per-node).
- A reconnecting node's subscribers MUST re-subscribe explicitly. The library does not cache subscriptions across disconnects.

### 9.4 Optional cluster-wide rotation events

For operational visibility across a fleet, the library SHOULD provide an opt-in mechanism to broadcast rotation events cluster-wide using `:pg` (ships with OTP, no external dep):

```elixir
config :rotating_secrets,
  cluster_broadcast: true,
  cluster_broadcast_group: :rotating_secrets_rotations
```

When enabled, each rotation emits `{:rotating_secret_rotated_cluster, node(), name, version}` to the `:pg` group. Messages carry node, name, and version — **never the value**.

**Requirements:**
- Cluster broadcasting MUST be opt-in and default-off.
- `:pg` is used (not Phoenix.PubSub) to keep the library dependency-free.
- Broadcast failures (e.g., `:pg` not started, node partitioned) MUST NOT affect local rotation behavior.

### 9.5 Cluster status inspection

```elixir
@spec cluster_status(name :: atom()) :: %{node() => {:ok, version :: term(), meta :: map()} | {:error, term()}}
```

Returns the current version and metadata for `name` on each connected node. Uses `:rpc.multicall/4` with a short timeout; unreachable nodes return `{:error, :noconnection}`.

Intended for operational tooling, not hot-path code. Secret values are NEVER returned.

## 10. Testing Requirements

The library MUST ship with:

- Unit tests per module, ≥90% line coverage on core.
- Property tests via `StreamData` for:
  - Rotation consistency: rotating at arbitrary points during concurrent reads never yields a torn value.
  - Fail-soft: arbitrary sequences of `load/1` failures never produce a crash or an empty response after initial success.
  - Version monotonicity: no observer sees a version number decrease.
  - Subscriber fanout: N subscribers all receive rotation notifications under load.
- Integration tests using `Source.File`:
  - Atomic rename triggers reload.
  - Concurrent reads during rotation see old-or-new, never nil, never error.
- Log capture tests verifying no code path logs secret values.
- Telemetry event assertion tests.
- Multi-node tests using `LocalCluster` or equivalent:
  - Independent Registries on two nodes converge on the same version after rotation.
  - Horde-registered Registry correctly migrates; subscribers continue to receive events after migration.
  - Subscribers on a disconnecting node are cleaned up; reconnecting nodes must re-subscribe.
  - `:pg` cluster broadcast, when enabled, fires on each node.
  - Netsplit: both sides continue serving; healing causes no errors.
  - `cluster_status/1` handles unreachable nodes correctly.

